@Node Numbers "Device Handler - Number conversion"

  @{b}Number conversion@{ub}

  Any number which is to pass to the handler may start with '$' or '0x'
  or '0X' to indicate hexadecimal notation (default is decimal). A
  trailing 'M' tells the handler to interprete it as a mega-value, (i.e.
  multiply by 1024^2) and 'K' to signal a kilo value (factor 1024). All
  charactes are case-insensitive.

  @{b}Examples@{ub}

     1k,1K,$400,0x400,0X400   mean all 1 KB = 1024 Byte
     1M,1024K                 mean all 1 MB = 1024 KB = 1048576 Byte

@EndNode

@Node StreamConversion "Device Handler - Stream name conversion"

  @{b}Stream name conversion@{ub}

  The following steps are performed during stream name conversion:

  1. All slashes are removed and replaced by blanks.

  2. All dots ('.'), that appear @{i}after the first slash@{ui} and which
     are not part of a quoted text, are substituted by an equation symbol
     ('='). That comes in handy when using the LOCYL or HICYL options.
     AmigaDOS strips all equations that are not quoted. Thus, the command
     "type dev:df0/locyl=3" would lead to an error, as the handler would
     get the text "dev:df0/locyl" instead of "dev:df0/locyl=3". So, either
     use the dot or quote the whole stream specification.

@EndNode

